                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding>
                                <p>Early modern binding. Light brown leather over wooden boards. 4 double raised bands and endbands. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>, stamped in gold: <quote>A 224</quote>.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="310" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="225" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="60" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <decoNote type="tooling">
                                    <p>Simple blind tooled decoration consisting of panels and x-shapes.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                                <condition>According to a librarian's note from the 19th century the binding has been repaired. The front cover had been detached and the spine was very worn. Before the repair the spine had a sticker attached to it, on which <quote>n<hi rend="super">o</hi> 18</quote> was written.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName cert="low" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100036">Italy</placeName>
                                </origPlace>, <origDate notAfter="1600" notBefore="1401">15th-16th century. </origDate>Origin and dating conjecture based on the script.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Exact origin and early provenance unknown. The manuscript has been at the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">National LIbrary</orgName>since the 17th century. The two signa on <locus from="1r" to="1r" scheme="folios"/> refers to Jaches's catalgoue of 1698 (U 122), where it is listed as <quote>214</quote>; and the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e), where it is listed as <quote>Theol. in 4<hi rend="super">o</hi> nr 8</quote>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
